    "summary": "The Qin Standardization of Measures (221–210 BC) was [[event:3141|Qin Shi Huang]]'s sweeping unification of weights, measures, currency, and writing across the newly unified empire — a bureaucratic revolution that made the diverse conquered territories function as a single economic and administrative unit.\n\nBefore unification, each of the seven warring states used different currencies, different standards for weights and measures, and different forms of Chinese script. Commerce between regions was hampered and administration was inconsistent. Qin's standardizations included: a unified weight system based on bronze weights; standardized axle widths for carts (ensuring all roads were usable by all vehicles); a unified round bronze coin with square hole; and most consequentially, a standardized form of Chinese writing (the Small Seal script) that allowed bureaucrats from any region to communicate with each other and with the central government. The writing standardization had enduring importance: while spoken Chinese dialects diverged dramatically over centuries, the shared written language created a cultural unity that persisted despite political fragmentation. These reforms, implemented by chancellor Li Si, were among the most transformative administrative acts in Chinese history.",
